ecutionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1775718039034,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":51,"user":{"displayName":"","userId":""}},"outputId":"17597be1-922e-42e1-9daa-8ed44c390b1f"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["7.169321280162059\n"]}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["crit = stats.chi2.ppf(q = 0.95, # Find the critical value for 95% confidence*\n","                      df = 8)   # *\n","\n","print(\"Critical value\")\n","print(crit)\n","\n","p_value = 1 - stats.chi2.cdf(x=chi_squared_stat,  # Find the p-value\n","                             df=8)\n","print(\"P value\")\n","print(p_value)"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"z3qgKN02Czwn","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1775718058201,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":15,"user":{"displayName":"","userId":""}},"outputId":"53f0858c-840c-4635-97ac-39b0fa1171f1"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["Critical value\n","15.50731305586545\n","P value\n","0.518479392948842\n"]}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["stats.chi2_contingency(observed= observed)"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"B9cYKiOYC4lr","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1775718078017,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":44,"user":{"displayName":"","userId":""}},"outputId":"d2b0a101-fd76-4fc5-e048-76242c14a7fc"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["Chi2ContingencyResult(statistic=np.float64(7.169321280162059), pvalue=np.float64(0.518479392948842), dof=8, expected_freq=array([[ 23.82 ,  11.16 ,  25.02 ],\n","       [ 61.138,  28.644,  64.218],\n","       [ 99.647,  46.686, 104.667],\n","       [ 15.086,   7.068,  15.846],\n","       [197.309,  92.442, 207.249]]))"]},"metadata":{},"execution_count":10}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["The output shows the chi-square statistic, the p-value and the degrees of freedom followed by the expected counts.\n","\n","As expected, given the high p-value, the test result does not detect a significant relationship between the variables."],"metadata":{"id":"f-OTsQpeC_EU"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**1.When do we go for Chi-square test?**\n","\n","The Chi-squared test is primarily used for categorical data. There are two main types:\n","\n","Chi-squared Goodness-of-Fit Test: Used to determine if the observed distribution of a single categorical variable in a sample matches an expected or theoretical distribution (e.g., does the distribution of colors in a bag of candies match what the manufacturer claims?).\n","Chi-squared Test of Independence: Used to determine if there is a statistically significant association between two categorical variables (e.g., is there a relationship between gender and preferred type of car?).\n","**2.Do we use Chi-square test for independence?** **Explain How?**\n","\n","Yes, the Chi-squared test of independence is specifically designed for this purpose. It works by comparing the observed frequencies in a contingency table (a table that displays the frequency distribution of the variables) with the expected frequencies. The expected frequencies are what you would anticipate if there were no relationship (i.e., if the variables were independent).\n","\n","How it works: You calculate a Chi-squared statistic based on the differences between observed and expected counts. A large difference indicates that the observed data deviates significantly from what would be expected under independence, suggesting a relationship between the variables.\n","**3.Explain role of Critical value and p-value in Chi-square test.**\n","\n","Both the critical value and p-value are used to make a decision about your hypothesis:\n","\n","Critical Value: This is a threshold value obtained from the Chi-squared distribution table for a given significance level (alpha, commonly 0.05) and degrees of freedom. If your calculated Chi-squared statistic is greater than the critical value, you reject the null hypothesis (which states that there is no relationship/difference).\n","P-value: The p-value is the probability of observing a test statistic as extreme as, or more extreme than, the one calculated from your sample, assuming the null hypothesis is true. If the p-value is less than your chosen significance level (alpha, e.g., 0.05), you reject the null hypothesis. A small p-value indicates strong evidence against the null hypothesis.\n","In essence, both methods lead to the same conclusion: if your test statistic is in the\n","**4.Can we use the Chi-squared test to show the existence of correlation between 2 features in a dataset? How will you interpret test results to indicate correlation presence? **\n","\n","Yes, the Chi-squared test of independence is used to assess if there's an association (or dependence) between two categorical features. While 'correlation' often implies a linear relationship between numeric variables, in the context of categorical variables, an association or dependence is the equivalent concept. If two categorical variables are associated, it means that the distribution of one variable differs depending on the value of the other variable.\n","\n","Interpreting test results for correlation/association: When you perform a Chi-squared test of independence, your null hypothesis ($H_0$$H_0$) is that there is no association between the two categorical variables (i.e., they are independent). The alternative hypothesis ($H_1$$H_1$) is that there is an association between them.\n","If the p-value is less than your chosen significance level (e.g., 0.05), you reject the null hypothesis. This suggests that there is statistically significant evidence to conclude that an association exists between the two categorical features in your dataset. In simpler terms, the features are likely related.\n","If the Chi-squared statistic is greater than the critical value, you also reject the null hypothesis, leading to the same conclusion.\n","**5.What are degrees of freedom and how to calculate it while performing a Chi-squared test?**\n","\n","Degrees of Freedom (df) refers to the number of independent pieces of information that go into calculating a statistic. In simpler terms, it's the number of values in a study that are free to vary. It's a crucial component because it helps determine the shape of the Chi-squared distribution, which in turn affects the critical value and p-value.\n","\n","Calculation for Chi-squared Goodness-of-Fit Test: For a goodness-of-fit test, where you are comparing observed frequencies of a single categorical variable to expected frequencies: df = (number of categories - 1) For example, if you have 5 categories (like 'asian', 'black', 'hispanic', 'other', 'white' in our earlier example), the degrees of freedom would be 5 - 1 = 4.\n","\n","Calculation for Chi-squared Test of Independence: For a test of independence, where you are examining the relationship between two categorical variables in a contingency table: df = (number of rows - 1) * (number of columns - 1) Here, 'rows' and 'columns' refer to the number of categories for each of the two categorical variables being tested (excluding any total rows or columns). For instance, if you have a 5x3 contingency table (like our voter race vs. party example with 5 races and 3 parties), the degrees of freedom would be (5 - 1) * (3 - 1) = 4 * 2 = 8.\n","\n","\n"],"metadata":{"id":"esowyI3LDQnu"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":[],"metadata":{"id":"mDRSLPcTBHkb"}}],"metadata":{"colab":{"provenance":[{"file_id":"1Smbq6SyEQ_O2HVWKxCrbgmQQ8q7DzzOS","timestamp":1775718606495},{"file_id":"/v2/external/notebooks/intro.ipynb","timestamp":1775718581919}]},"kernelspec":{"display_name":"Python 3","name":"python3"}},"nbformat":4,"nbformat_minor":0}